    "\n",
    "# Tic-Tac-Toe Lab Design (Student Version)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Goal:** Design the system before writing code.\n",
    "\n",
    "Assumption: **X always goes first.**\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 1) Tic-Tac-Toe as a System\n",
    "A system has:\n",
    "- State (the data we track)\n",
    "- Transitions (actions that change state)\n",
    "- Invariants (rules that must always hold)\n",
    "- Inspection functions (ways to query state without changing it)\n",
    "\n",
    "Write 2–3 sentences: What makes this a "system"?\n",
    "\n",
    "Tic-tac-toe is a system because it has state (the board with X's and O's), transitions (placing a move changes the board), and invariants (like players must alternate turns). The game follows strict rules about what moves are valid and when it ends, which makes it a well-defined system you can model with code.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 2) Essential State vs Derived State\n",
    "\n",
    "## Essential (Required) State\n",
    "Essential state is information you **must store** because you cannot reconstruct it.\n",
    "\n",
    "Question:\n",
    "If the program stopped right now, what must be saved to resume the game?\n",
    "\n",
    "Essential state:\n",
    "\n",
    "- The board (3x3 grid showing where X's and O's are placed)\n",
    "\n",
    "Why is that enough?\n",
    "\n",
    "Since X always goes first, you can figure out whose turn it is just by counting. If theres an equal number of X's and O's, its X's turn. If X has one more than O, its O's turn. So the board alone is enough to reconstruct everything.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## Derived State (Convenience)\n",
    "Derived state is information you can compute from essential state.\n",
    "It often exists for convenience/readability.\n",
    "\n",
    "List 3 derived values you might compute from the board:\n",
    "\n",
    "1) Current player (X or O) - derived from counting symbols\n",
    "2) Winner (X, O, or None) - derived from checking rows/cols/diagonals\n",
    "3) Is the board full - derived from counting empty spaces\n",
    "\n",
    "Why might we still compute/store derived values?\n",
    "\n",
    "Its more readable to call `current_player(board)` than to write out the counting logic every time. Also avoids bugs from copy-pasting the same logic in multiple places.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 3) Transitions vs Inspection (State Queries)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Transition functions\n",
    "Transitions **mutate** state (change the board).\n",
    "\n",
    "List the transition function(s) for Tic-Tac-Toe:\n",
    "\n",
    "- place_move(board, row, col, player) - this is the only one that actually changes the board\n",
    "\n",
    "## Inspection functions\n",
    "Inspections **interrogate** state (read the board, do not change it).\n",
    "\n",
    "List 3 inspection functions:\n",
    "\n",
    "1) is_valid_move(board, row, col) - checks if a square is empty and in bounds\n",
    "2) check_winner(board) - looks for three in a row\n",
    "3) game_over(board) - checks if theres a winner or the board is full\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 4) `game_over(board)` (Inspection Wrapper)\n",
    "\n",
    "We can avoid repeating the stopping condition by writing a helper:\n",
    "\n",
    "`game_over(board)` should return True when the game is over.\n",
    "\n",
    "Write in words what it should check:\n",
    "\n",
    "Check if there's a winner (someone got three in a row), OR if the board is completely full with no empty spaces. If either is true, the game is over.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 5) Human move vs Computer move (Decision Logic)\n",
    "\n",
    "Choosing a move is **decision logic**, not a state change.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why might we want *two* functions?\n",
    "\n",
    "- `get_human_move(board)`\n",
    "- `get_computer_move(board)`\n",
    "\n",
    "Write 1–2 sentences:\n",
    "\n",
    "They get input from different sources. The human version needs to read from keyboard input and validate what the user typed, while the computer version uses some algorithm to pick a move (could be random, could be smart). Separating them makes the code cleaner.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 6) Invariants\n",
    "\n",
    "## Structural invariants (shape/allowed values)\n",
    "List 2 structural invariants:\n",
    "\n",
    "1) Board is always 3x3 (9 cells total)\n",
    "2) Each cell contains only 'X', 'O', or ' ' (empty space)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Logical invariants (rules that must always hold)\n",
    "List 3 logical invariants:\n",
    "\n",
    "1) X count equals O count, OR X count equals O count + 1 (since X goes first)\n",
    "2) Once a cell has X or O, it cant be changed or overwritten\n",
    "3) Game stops as soon as someone wins - no more moves after that\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# 7) Architecture Sketch (Fill in the labels)\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "            +-------------------+\n",
    "            |     main_loop     |   (controller / main loop)\n",
    "            +-------------------+\n",
    "                 |         |\n",
    "                 |         +-----------------------+\n",
    "                 |                                 |\n",
    "        (decision logic                           |\n",
    "         chooses which                             |\n",
    "         transition to                            |\n",
    "         apply)                              (inspection)\n",
    "     +-------------------+              +-------------------+\n",
    "     | get_human_move    |              | is_valid_move     |\n",
    "     +-------------------+              +-------------------+\n",
    "     | get_computer_move |              | check_winner      |\n",
    "     +-------------------+              | game_over         |\n",
    "                 |                      +-------------------+\n",
    "                 |\n",
    "           (transition)\n",
    "     +-------------------+\n",
    "     | place_move        |   <-- ONLY function that mutates board\n",
    "     +-------------------+\n",
    "                 |\n",
    "               board\n",
    "```\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 8) Program Flow Diagram\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "    START\n",
    "    │\n",
    "    ├── board = create_board()\n",
    "    ├── player = O\n",
    "    │\n",
    "    └── WHILE True:\n",
    "        │\n",
    "        ├── clear_screen()\n",
    "        ├── display_board(board)\n",
    "        │\n",
    "        ├── if game_over(board):\n",
    "        │        print_result()\n",
    "        │        break\n",
    "        │\n",
    "        ├── player = switch_player(player)\n",
    "        │\n",
    "        ├── if player == X:\n",
    "        │        move = get_human_move(board)\n",
    "        │    else:\n",
    "        │        move = get_computer_move(board)\n",
    "        │\n",
    "        ├── if not is_valid_move(board, move):\n",
    "        │        continue\n",
    "        │\n",
    "        └── place_move(board, move, player)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
